			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/25/opinion/nyto-sharing/nyto-sharing-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/25/opinion/nyto-sharing/nyto-sharing-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/25/opinion/nyto-sharing/nyto-sharing-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002963207" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew Quilty for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/25/even-advice-isnt-free-anymore/" data-title="Even Advice Isn&#8217;t Free Anymore" data-description="Some people are charging for the kind of career advice once offered for free, and the growing freelance economy may be to blame, ANNA NORTH writes.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Are your friends always coming to you for advice? Maybe you could start a business. Charging for what might once have been informal counsel is becoming more common â and the growing freelance economy may be behind the shift.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At The New York Post, Anna Davies <a href="//nypost.com/2014/06/22/want-to-network-over-a-cup-of-coffee-its-going-to-cost-you/">writes</a>, âRecently I received a request from a young writer who followed me on Twitter asking if she could âpick my brainâ about various writing opportunities in New York City.â She turned the young writer down â and found many who had begun charging for the privilege of picking. Marissa Vicario, a health coach, tells her:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAs my business has become more successful and my public persona has increased, Iâve increasingly received emails from others in my field who essentially want to do the same thing Iâm doing. While I love mentoring, I value my time and expertise and have started to charge. Iâve found that those who value my time and expertise are happy to pay the fee.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others have been less supportive of the pay-for-advice idea. At The Billfold, Mike Dang <a href="//thebillfold.com/2014/06/a-pick-your-brain-fee/">writes</a>:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âPeople have asked to meet me for coffee before. I have said yes. If I am busy, I say no, but suggest that the person try again in the future when things are calmer. I see it as paying it forward â plenty of people have agreed to meet me and provide me with advice, so I have been happy to do the same.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And the management and psychology professor Adam Grant has argued that offering help could end up benefiting the helper â in a recent Atlantic article, he <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/how-to-succeed-professionally-by-helping-others/284429/">wrote</a>:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBeing a âgiverâ who enjoys helping others can be inefficient in the short run but surprisingly productive in the long run. Givers tend to start out with lower sales revenue and lower medical school grades. In sales, givers often put their customersâ needs above their own sales targets. In medicine, before big exams, givers are so busy helping their friends study that they fail to fill the holes in their own understanding. Yet after a year in sales, the highest revenue belongs to those same generous people, and by the end of medical school, the top grades belong to the students with the most passion for helping others.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elsewhere, though, anti-brain-picking sentiment has been building for some time. Last year, Marie Forleo, who gives training to entrepreneurs, offeredÂ <a href="//www.marieforleo.com/2013/06/pick-your-brain/#ixzz35f02d9e6">advice</a>Â for those âdrowning in constant requests from friends who want to âhave coffee and pick your brain.ââ She wrote:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe truth isâ¦<br />
a. You donât freakinâ have time for coffee right now.<br />
b. You donât want to have your brain picked.<br />
c. And, if you did, youâd wanna get paid for it!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And in a 2011 post at Forbes, Adrienne GrahamÂ <a href="//www.forbes.com/sites/work-in-progress/2011/03/28/no-you-cant-pick-my-brain-it-costs-too-much/">outlined</a>Â her response to brain-picking requests:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âNot gonna happen, sorry. My brain costs money to maintain. Thereâs training, classes to attend, reading (I have to buy books), gaining certifications, costs of memberships so I can network, attending conferences and mastering my skills that all cost me money.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI have to protect my investment. How fair is it to me to give away all the knowledge I have acquired that I use to make my living, pay my bills and eat?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Davies attributes the charging-for-advice trend to the rise of freelancing: âA large part of the commercialization of mentoring sessions may be because there are simply more self-employed types than ever before, especially in creative fields.â She explains that âcreative freelancers are finding that adding consulting to their list of marketable skills can boost their cash flow.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The growth of freelancing may also have fed demand for advice in the first place. While those who work in offices may be able to buttonhole their colleagues with questions, people working for themselves may have to seek out friends or acquaintances for help. The brain-picking coffee may be the new water-cooler conversation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In her dispiriting Fast Company account of her month in the freelance âgig economy,â Sarah Kessler <a href="//www.fastcompany.com/3027355/pixel-and-dimed-on-not-getting-by-in-the-gig-economy">writes</a> about forgoing many of the protections offered by traditional employers, like insurance. A manager at one gig-economy startup told her: âYou are not an employee of Postmates. So when it comes to safety, you are on your own.â Indeed, she finds, âthe âon your ownâ answer applies to everything about the job.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To some degree, it may apply to life as a freelancer in general. Though freelancers are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/10/nyregion/for-freelancers-in-the-gig-economy-a-mix-of-freedom-and-uncertainty.html">banding together</a>Â in groups like the Freelancers Union for the purposes of negotiation and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/03/24/business/freelancers-union-tackles-concerns-of-independent-workers.html?pagewanted=all&amp;module=Search&amp;mabReward=relbias%3Ar%2C%5B%22RI%3A5%22%2C%22RI%3A14%22%5D">mutual support</a>, those outside such networks may find help hard to come by. And those trying to make a living on their own may feel they need to charge for anything they can, brain picking included.</p>
	</div>
